# CLAUDE.md

This file provides guidance to Claude Code (claude.ai/code) when working with code in this repository.

## What this is

{{ app_title }} — generated from the [cloudflare-better-auth-d1 copier template](https://copier.readthedocs.io/). Adapts the [Hono + Better Auth](https://hono.dev/examples/better-auth-on-cloudflare) recipe to use **Cloudflare D1** instead of Neon. One Cloudflare Worker serves both the Better Auth API and a Vite React SPA.

## Layout

```
.                  # Hono Worker (Better Auth on D1)
  src/index.ts              Hono app, mounts /api/auth/* on the better-auth handler
  src/lib/better-auth/      auth() factory — drizzleAdapter(drizzle(env.DB), 'sqlite')
  src/db/schema.ts          GENERATED by @better-auth/cli — do not edit by hand
  drizzle/                  SQL migrations generated by drizzle-kit from schema.ts
  wrangler.jsonc            D1 binding `DB`, assets binding `ASSETS` → ./web/dist
  better-auth.config.ts     Schema-generation config (uses better-sqlite3 :memory:)
  drizzle.config.ts         dialect: sqlite, driver: d1-http

web/               # Vite React SPA (shadcn preset buFznsW, radix-lyra, phosphor icons)
  src/App.tsx               Auth-gated root (loading → dashboard or login card)
  src/components/login-card.tsx, dashboard.tsx
  src/lib/auth-client.ts    Thin fetch wrapper hitting /api/auth/*
```

Worker serves the SPA through the `assets` binding with `not_found_handling: single-page-application`. `run_worker_first: ["/api/*"]` gates the Worker in front of the assets handler for API routes.

## Commands (mise tasks)

All project commands run through mise — see `mise.toml` for the full list, or `mise tasks`.

First-run checklist (copier's `_tasks` already ran `mise trust`, `mise install`, and the JS installs on render):

```bash
bunx wrangler login       # one-time CF auth (skip if you're going headless)
mise init                 # seeds .dev.vars, applies local migrations, and — if
                          # wrangler is authenticated — provisions the remote D1
                          # (patching wrangler.jsonc), BETTER_AUTH_SECRET, and
                          # remote migrations
mise dev                  # http://localhost:8787
mise deploy               # ship to *.workers.dev
```

Common loops:

```bash
mise run dev              # builds SPA (source-tracked) then wrangler dev
mise run typecheck        # Worker + web together
mise run web:build        # SPA only; mise caches based on sources
mise run deploy           # web:build -> wrangler deploy
```

For a fresh worktree (e.g. fulcrum task branch) where you want production-like data without touching remote resources:

```bash
mise run worktree-init    # deps + .dev.vars + wipe & re-migrate local D1 +
                          # pull prod data via read-only `wrangler d1 export --remote`
```

The export goes through D1's R2-staged export endpoint and is applied locally via the `sqlite3` CLI (bypasses wrangler's ~1MB per-statement limit on local execute). If the project adds FTS or other virtual tables, narrow `wrangler d1 export` with `--table=<name>` flags so local triggers — not exported shadow-table INSERTs — populate the index.

## Schema & migration flow

The schema is **generated, not hand-written**. When adding a better-auth plugin or changing `src/lib/better-auth/options.ts`:

```bash
mise run auth:generate    # regenerates src/db/schema.ts from better-auth.config.ts
mise run db:generate      # drizzle-kit turns schema.ts into drizzle/NNNN_*.sql
mise run migrate:local    # wrangler d1 migrations apply --local
```

Remote D1 migrations apply automatically on push to `main` when Workers Builds is connected (see the Deploy section) — `bun run ci:build` runs `db:migrate:remote` before `wrangler deploy`. `mise run migrate:remote` / `bun run db:migrate:remote` remain available as an escape hatch for out-of-band fixes or local `mise deploy`.

Ordering inside `ci:build`: install deps → build SPA → apply D1 migrations → (Workers Builds then runs `wrangler deploy`). D1 lands before the Worker, so migrations must stay forward-compatible with the currently-deployed Worker — destructive schema changes require two pushes (first push: code tolerating both schemas; second push: the drop).

Non-production branches run `ci:build:preview` instead, which is `ci:build` **without** `db:migrate:remote`. PR previews share the production D1, so an unreviewed migration must not land there; preview builds therefore run the new code against the *current* schema. A PR that needs a new column won't fully work in preview until the PR merges and `main` deploys — that's by design.

`better-auth.config.ts` uses an in-memory `better-sqlite3` DB because the CLI doesn't need a real connection to emit drizzle table definitions — only the adapter shape.

## Deploy

Two paths. **Local ad-hoc:**

```bash
mise deploy
```

**Push to deploy (recommended once the project is on GitHub):**

```bash
mise run builds:connect
```

Idempotently calls the Cloudflare API to attach this repo to `{{ worker_name }}` and create two triggers:

- `main` → `bun run ci:build` → `wrangler deploy` (production)
- all other branches → `bun run ci:build:preview` → `wrangler versions upload` (preview-only version; does not replace production)

One-time prerequisite: install the [Cloudflare Workers & Pages GitHub App](https://github.com/apps/cloudflare-workers-and-pages) on the repo's owner. The task detects an unauthorized app and prints the install link.

**Why two triggers.** Workers Builds has no "production branch" flag or "all non-production branches" API toggle — the dashboard's "Builds for non-production branches" checkbox is implemented as a second trigger with `branch_includes: ["*"]` + `branch_excludes: ["main"]`. The API also rejects that shape on PATCH of an existing main-only trigger; you have to create both triggers up front via POST. `branch_includes: ["*"]` alone (without `branch_excludes`) is rejected with error 12002.

**Preview URLs.** `preview_urls: true` in `wrangler.jsonc` gives every version stable URLs:

- `https://<version-id>-{{ worker_name }}.<subdomain>.workers.dev`
- `https://<branch>-{{ worker_name }}.<subdomain>.workers.dev`

Workers Builds auto-comments both on the PR.

**Durable Objects fallback.** Cloudflare disables those preview URLs whenever the Worker has a DO binding (DO state is global per-Worker; there's no per-version partitioning). `.github/workflows/preview.yml` covers the gap: if it sees `durable_objects.bindings` in `wrangler.jsonc`, it deploys a per-PR Worker named `{{ worker_name }}-pr-<n>` and sticky-comments the URL on the PR. Each PR's Worker is its own DO namespace by construction, so PRs can't trample each other's state. The preview shares the production D1 (same `database_id`) and skips migrations — same trade-off as the Workers Builds preview path. Without DOs the workflow no-ops so it doesn't clobber Workers Builds. `.github/workflows/preview-cleanup.yml` deletes the preview Worker on PR close. Required repo secrets: `CLOUDFLARE_API_TOKEN` (Workers Scripts: Edit + D1: Edit) **or** `CLOUDFLARE_API_KEY` + `CLOUDFLARE_EMAIL` (global key fallback), plus `CLOUDFLARE_ACCOUNT_ID`.

`mise init` already uploaded `BETTER_AUTH_SECRET` and applied remote migrations. `mise run secret:put` (idempotent) rotates the secret.

`mise deploy` auto-patches `vars.BETTER_AUTH_URL` in `wrangler.jsonc` from the `*.workers.dev` URL that wrangler prints on the first deploy, then redeploys once so the Worker's origin matches the URL better-auth uses for redirects and cookies. Override it manually beforehand if you're fronting with a custom domain.

The Worker serves `web/dist`, so SPA edits need a rebuild before they're visible. `mise run dev` handles this automatically: it does an initial `web:build`, then runs `vite build --watch` in the background alongside `wrangler dev`, so SPA source changes incrementally rebuild `web/dist` and the next page reload picks them up. The watcher is process-grouped via `trap` so Ctrl+C cleans both halves up.

## Auth-specific gotchas

- Better Auth requires `env.BETTER_AUTH_SECRET` (a wrangler secret) and `env.BETTER_AUTH_URL`. The Env type is augmented in `src/env.d.ts` to include `BETTER_AUTH_SECRET` since it's not in `wrangler.jsonc`.
- `options.ts` sets `advanced.ipAddress.ipAddressHeaders: ["cf-connecting-ip"]` — without this better-auth logs rate-limiter warnings on Workers.
- `auth-client.ts` POSTs `body: "{}"` on sign-out because better-auth parses the body as JSON and crashes on an empty stream.
- The auth handler expects `basePath: "/api/auth"` matching the Hono route mount.
- Better Auth's CSRF check ("Invalid origin") rejects any request whose Origin doesn't match `BETTER_AUTH_URL` or an entry in `trustedOrigins`. `src/lib/better-auth/index.ts` builds that list with two layers: it auto-derives `https://*.<sub>.workers.dev` whenever `BETTER_AUTH_URL` itself is on workers.dev (so Workers Builds preview URLs work zero-config), and it merges in any extras from the comma-separated `BETTER_AUTH_TRUSTED_ORIGINS` env var. Set that var in `wrangler.jsonc` `vars` for custom-domain prod (covering workers.dev preview URLs the auto-derive can't see), or in `.dev.vars` for local dev when you hit the Worker via a hostname that doesn't match `BETTER_AUTH_URL` (a `/etc/hosts` entry, reverse proxy, alternate port). Prefer adding the alternate origin to `BETTER_AUTH_TRUSTED_ORIGINS` over editing `BETTER_AUTH_URL` so cookies stay on the canonical origin.
